We are all gonna become rheumatologist here

7
00:00:25.260 --> 00:00:26.433
in the next 30 minutes.

8
00:00:29.970 --> 00:00:34.440
We could spend a whole weekend talking about rheumatology.

9
00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:37.320
These are the things that are the most common questions

10
00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:39.390
on the boards, and they're the most common things

11
00:00:39.390 --> 00:00:40.890
that we see in practice too.

12
00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:42.540
So we'll hit the highlights

13
00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:47.460
of the major arthritic processes, RA, OA,

14
00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:51.330
the spondyloarthropathies, gout,

15
00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:55.680
and then we'll talk about treatment.

16
00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:58.560
34-year-old female with a history of lupus

17
00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:01.920
comes in with acute pain, rubor, calor,

18
00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:04.170
and swelling in her left knee.

19
00:01:04.170 --> 00:01:06.780
She denies any recent trauma and is currently taking

20
00:01:06.780 --> 00:01:09.840
hydroxychloroquine and prednisone.

21
00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:13.260
Her other SLE symptoms have been well-controlled overall.

22
00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:18.260
The most likely cause of this patient's knee pain is,

23
00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:20.943
A, is it an infectious process?

24
00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:24.930
Is it a patellofemoral syndrome?

25
00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:26.073
Is it RA?

26
00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:29.643
Or is this an SLE flare?

27
00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:37.350
All right, let's see what we got.

28
00:01:37.350 --> 00:01:40.650
So this is a learning opportunity here.

29
00:01:40.650 --> 00:01:42.810
Most of you got this right, infectious arthritis.

30
00:01:42.810 --> 00:01:45.600
This is the most important diagnosis to make.

31
00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:47.700
And Dr. Gary was referring to this

32
00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:49.860
when he was talking about the synovitis

33
00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:51.300
versus an infectious process.

34
00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:55.230
But identifying a monoarticular joint

35
00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:59.160
that could be infected is the first question

36
00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:00.060
that you should ask.

37
00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:02.520
Is it an infection or not?

38
00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:04.380
In general, when you're looking at

39
00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:08.520
all of the articular diseases, and there are so many,

40
00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:10.920
try to put them in one of three buckets.

41
00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:14.520
So is it a monoarticular process, as in this patient?

42
00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:18.060
Is it a symmetric polyarticular process?

43
00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:22.083
Or is it an asymmetric polyarticular process?

44
00:02:23.670 --> 00:02:27.900
So this was the acute monoarthritis, that was an infection.

45
00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:31.800
So the most critical diagnosis to make.

46
00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:36.780
It's an inflammation, the rubor, calor in one single joint.

47
00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:39.960
Most commonly, it's gonna be strep

48
00:02:39.960 --> 00:02:44.493
followed by MRSA, and then GAS and GBS in adults.

49
00:02:46.860 --> 00:02:49.050
So this is a list of all the different possibilities

50
00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:52.320
to think about when you're imagining the differential

51
00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:54.570
with a common monoarticular process.

52
00:02:54.570 --> 00:02:58.050
So these are usually the non-rheumatologic ones,

53
00:02:58.050 --> 00:03:01.530
although sometimes you can have a, you know, RA can,

54
00:03:01.530 --> 00:03:03.690
or JRA can start with a single joint.

55
00:03:03.690 --> 00:03:05.550
Most of the time they don't.

56
00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:10.440
So the common monoarticular ones are these like crystals.

57
00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:12.690
Is that OA in a single joint?

58
00:03:12.690 --> 00:03:15.453
Trauma was their previous infection.

59
00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:18.110
Don't forget to consider neoplasm.

60
00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:20.580
Is this an overuse injury?

61
00:03:20.580 --> 00:03:23.150
Or is this some type of vascular process

62
00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:24.300
in that single joint?

63
00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:25.410
And we'll come back and talk about

64
00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:27.930
all the other ones here briefly.

65
00:03:27.930 --> 00:03:31.233
These are the symmetric polyarthritides.

66
00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:34.650
Most of them you notice are

67
00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:37.680
have some rheumatologic component, but not all of them.

68
00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:39.840
We'll come back to RA.

69
00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:42.510
We're not gonna talk much about SLE today.

70
00:03:42.510 --> 00:03:44.820
So I would encourage you to go back at some point,

71
00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:46.893
and just take a peek at SLE.

72
00:03:47.970 --> 00:03:52.230
Remembering that they have commonly found skin findings.

73
00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:54.720
PMR, we're not gonna talk about today either.

74
00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:58.710
But PMR is something to go back and take a quick review.

75
00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:01.650
Most commonly affecting the proximal muscles

76
00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:04.980
in the shoulders and in your hip flexors.

77
00:04:04.980 --> 00:04:08.820
Lyme's disease, there's a slide in your supplementary slides

78
00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:09.653
about Lymes.

79
00:04:09.653 --> 00:04:11.250
We're not gonna spend much time there.

80
00:04:11.250 --> 00:04:15.540
We'll come back to CPPD, pseudogout, sarcoid.

81
00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:18.660
Don't forget those hilar, the hilar lymphadenopathy.

82
00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:20.130
And then we'll come back to the

83
00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:22.620
spondyloarthropathies briefly.

84
00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:24.720
So just a moment to think about

85
00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:27.960
the mechanics of during your exam,

86
00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:31.260
if you wanna grab your right arm, you know,

87
00:04:31.260 --> 00:04:34.050
when you're thinking about active range of motion, you know,

88
00:04:34.050 --> 00:04:36.780
if you wanna stretch it out, active range of motion,

89
00:04:36.780 --> 00:04:38.880
you're talking about pain associated

90
00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:41.850
with a periarticular process.

91
00:04:41.850 --> 00:04:45.060
In contrast with a passive pain

92
00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:46.380
with passive range of motion,

93
00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:49.620
that's gonna be an intra-articular process.

94
00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:51.810
So is it passive or active?

95
00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:54.270
Is it a single joint or multiple joints?

96
00:04:54.270 --> 00:04:58.050
Is this a mechanical versus an inflammatory process?

97
00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:01.020
These three questions will help get you started

98
00:05:01.020 --> 00:05:04.200
towards building your differential.

99
00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:06.870
This is a good kinda review slide to put a star on

100
00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:08.310
thinking about some hallmark signs

101
00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:10.800
that make great board questions.

102
00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:12.450
Again, active range of motion.

103
00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:14.850
Thinking about the periarticular process.

104
00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:16.740
If you have eye involvement,

105
00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:18.990
think about an ankylosing spondylitis,

106
00:05:18.990 --> 00:05:23.220
that's your number one spondyloarthropathy.

107
00:05:23.220 --> 00:05:26.130
If you have a coagulopathy,

108
00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:28.020
think about a hemarthrosis.

109
00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:32.730
We'll come back to stones, diuretics, et cetera.

110
00:05:32.730 --> 00:05:35.400
That's gonna be more likely a gout process.

111
00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:37.290
There again is your hilar adenopathy

112
00:05:37.290 --> 00:05:39.390
associated with sarcoid.

113
00:05:39.390 --> 00:05:42.360
As in this first patient, this immunosuppressed patient,

114
00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:44.610
you always have to think about infection

115
00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:46.470
in septic arthritis.

116
00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:48.720
The insidious onset of pain,

117
00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:52.620
most commonly osteoarthritis.

118
00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:55.740
Was there a previous attack with resolution?

119
00:05:55.740 --> 00:05:58.563
Think crystals, think CPPD or gout.

120
00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:03.120
Skin lesions, think psoriatic arthritis.

121
00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:05.523
We'll come back to some of these again.

122
00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:08.160
But here's another question.

123
00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:12.660
It's a 59-year-old female presents with symptoms of fatigue,

124
00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:15.960
mild weight loss, morning stiffness in both hands

125
00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:17.790
lasting more than an hour.

126
00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:20.940
She notes worsening tenderness in her MCPs

127
00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:23.283
and her DIP's bilaterally.

128
00:06:24.240 --> 00:06:26.190
Which of the following is the most specific

129
00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:30.120
to the diagnosis of this inflammatory process?

130
00:06:30.120 --> 00:06:31.743
Is it a high ESR?

131
00:06:32.790 --> 00:06:34.713
A positive ANA?

132
00:06:35.610 --> 00:06:38.730
Rheumatoid joint erosions?

133
00:06:38.730 --> 00:06:40.803
Or a rheumatoid factor?

134
00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:46.623
Which is the most specific in making this diagnosis?

135
00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:54.113
Good.

136
00:06:54.113 --> 00:06:57.870
So this is kind of a test-taking question to think about.

137
00:06:57.870 --> 00:07:00.180
All of these other surrogate markers

138
00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:04.050
are fairly nonspecific overall.

139
00:07:04.050 --> 00:07:06.840
Joint erosion seen on x-ray

140
00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:09.600
will definitely be the most specific.

141
00:07:09.600 --> 00:07:14.100
So this is kind of a test-taking approach

142
00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:15.693
to this question.

143
00:07:16.650 --> 00:07:18.810
The other marker that we could have added here

144
00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:22.050
is the anti-citrullinated protein antibody,

145
00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:24.510
which happens to be the most specific

146
00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:27.960
of the biologic markers, the ECPA.

147
00:07:27.960 --> 00:07:29.310
That's your most specific.

148
00:07:29.310 --> 00:07:33.300
High ESR, positive ANA can be positive.

149
00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:37.500
Rheumatoid factor is positive in like 80%.

150
00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:40.920
But these joint erosion seen on radiograph

151
00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:43.773
are the most specific for sure.

152
00:07:45.750 --> 00:07:48.210
So when using the joint score classification,

153
00:07:48.210 --> 00:07:51.450
which of the following does not contribute

154
00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:55.586
towards a diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis?

155
00:07:55.586 --> 00:08:00.390
So A, 4 to 10 small joints affected.

156
00:08:00.390 --> 00:08:01.623
A positive sed rate.

157
00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:05.700
Duration of symptoms less than six weeks.

158
00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:09.963
Or there is your positive ACPA?

159
00:08:16.410 --> 00:08:18.420
Good, awesome.

160
00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:20.190
So all of these contribute

161
00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:21.840
except symptoms less than six weeks.

162
00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:26.100
So generally you would have symptoms greater than six weeks.

163
00:08:26.100 --> 00:08:28.443
But all of these others, positive ACPA,

164
00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:31.593
4 to 10 small joints.

165
00:08:32.610 --> 00:08:36.090
As you would see in the criteria for rheumatoid arthritis,

166
00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:40.440
which are broken down into four primary buckets.

167
00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:42.390
Number of small joints.

168
00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:44.910
Your serology, as we just mentioned.

169
00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:48.360
Your acute phase reactants, and the duration of symptoms.

170
00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:51.090
So you're gonna get more points greater than six

171
00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:54.540
as it rules you in unequivocally more points

172
00:08:54.540 --> 00:08:59.540
for increased number of small joints versus large joints.

173
00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:01.233
So this is a great way to,

174
00:09:02.850 --> 00:09:06.120
pretty easy way to diagnose rheumatoid arthritis,

175
00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:08.370
which generally isn't the diagnosis

176
00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:11.400
is not typically the problem, right?

177
00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:15.300
The problem since few of us have like immediate access

178
00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:18.543
to rheumatology is starting the therapy.

179
00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:22.140
Don't forget that their rheumatoid arthritis

180
00:09:22.140 --> 00:09:24.060
is both an intraarticular process,

181
00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:26.880
but it's also an extra articular process.

182
00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:28.950
So there are lots of things that happen outside

183
00:09:28.950 --> 00:09:31.500
of the joints with rheumatoid disease.

184
00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.990
In fact, most people who die of rheumatoid disease,

185
00:09:33.990 --> 00:09:35.700
they don't die because of their rheumatoid disease,

186
00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:37.860
they die from a heart attack.

187
00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:40.530
Because it's a chronic inflammatory process

188
00:09:40.530 --> 00:09:42.480
that contributes to CAD.

189
00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:44.550
But it also contributes to all these other things,

190
00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:47.250
because it can affect every organ system.

191
00:09:47.250 --> 00:09:49.503
So just to make a note of that.

192
00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:53.070
So you do make the diagnosis.

193
00:09:53.070 --> 00:09:55.470
You're pretty sure you've ruled them in

194
00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:57.420
with greater than six points,

195
00:09:57.420 --> 00:09:59.760
and you decide they have the disease.

196
00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:03.780
It's a Friday afternoon, what do you do?

197
00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:06.150
When should you start using the disease,

198
00:10:06.150 --> 00:10:10.143
modulating anti-rheumatic medications?

199
00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:13.473
Immediately?

200
00:10:14.610 --> 00:10:17.613
Following three months of NSAID conservative therapy?

201
00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:21.960
Following a five-day burst of steroids?

202
00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:24.750
Or only after the patient has failed conservative therapy?

203
00:10:24.750 --> 00:10:28.323
So when do you start a DMARD on a Friday afternoon?

204
00:10:33.930 --> 00:10:34.763
Good.

205
00:10:34.763 --> 00:10:36.270
So this is all in our wheelhouse, right?

206
00:10:36.270 --> 00:10:37.103
To start a DMARD.

207
00:10:37.103 --> 00:10:39.000
And we'll talk about the different types of DMARDs.

208
00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.110
But as soon as you make the diagnosis of RA,

209
00:10:42.110 --> 00:10:45.090
RA is a ticking time bomb.

210
00:10:45.090 --> 00:10:49.458
So joints matter, and the sooner you intervene,

211
00:10:49.458 --> 00:10:51.840
this is a concept that I don't,

212
00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:53.130
it took me a while to realize,

213
00:10:53.130 --> 00:10:57.180
but the sooner you intervene in an acute RA flare,

214
00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:58.950
whether it be the first one or the second one,

215
00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:02.430
or the third one, the greater the likelihood

216
00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:04.740
of having actual remission.

217
00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:09.000
So this is, you know, as neurons are to a stroke,

218
00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.650
you know, joints are to RA.

219
00:11:10.650 --> 00:11:14.010
And so the timeliness of initiating therapy

220
00:11:14.010 --> 00:11:15.903
is very, very important.

221
00:11:17.310 --> 00:11:18.990
So typically if it is a Friday afternoon,

222
00:11:18.990 --> 00:11:22.350
typically we would load them on steroids,

223
00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:25.410
but we would also start them on methotrexate.

224
00:11:25.410 --> 00:11:26.250
I don't know about you all,

225
00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:29.130
but in our community in Asheville,

226
00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:30.420
I mean there's like a six month wait

227
00:11:30.420 --> 00:11:32.640
to get into to rheumatology these days.

228
00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:34.380
It's almost impossible.

229
00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:37.710
And so most of us have become very familiar

230
00:11:37.710 --> 00:11:40.953
with how to treat RA without a rheumatologist.

231
00:11:41.850 --> 00:11:44.400
Don't hesitate to pull the trigger on methotrexate

232
00:11:44.400 --> 00:11:45.960
on that Friday afternoon.

233
00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:49.410
You typically start with 7.5 milligrams,

234
00:11:49.410 --> 00:11:53.190
but you wanna try to get up to 15 milligrams per week,

235
00:11:53.190 --> 00:11:57.120
not per day, but per week, within at least six weeks.

236
00:11:57.120 --> 00:11:58.650
So that's the goal.

237
00:11:58.650 --> 00:12:02.370
It's a fairly rapid titration of methotrexate

238
00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:06.030
along with your folic acid, which is very important.

239
00:12:06.030 --> 00:12:08.613
You don't wanna exceed 20 milligrams per week.

240
00:12:09.509 --> 00:12:13.530
And then you have your other arsenal of non-biologics.

241
00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:16.470
These are all on the table for you too.

242
00:12:16.470 --> 00:12:20.250
And say for example, you live in an area where you truly

243
00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:21.960
don't have any access to rheumatology,

244
00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:26.960
and you truly have difficulty like finding a biologic DMARD,

245
00:12:27.390 --> 00:12:30.540
then it's okay to use triple therapy.

246
00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:33.450
So triple therapy is very, very effective

247
00:12:33.450 --> 00:12:35.370
with non-biologic agents.

248
00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:39.513
So that would include primarily methotrexate, leflunomide,

249
00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:43.830
hydroxychloroquine, and sulfasalazine.

250
00:12:43.830 --> 00:12:48.720
So one of those, you can use three of those four initially.

251
00:12:48.720 --> 00:12:51.480
What you would just use methotrexate initially.

252
00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:53.160
If you don't get control,

253
00:12:53.160 --> 00:12:57.870
then you can use the triple therapy non-biologics,

254
00:12:57.870 --> 00:12:59.850
if you don't have access to a biologic.

255
00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:01.600
So that just something to consider.

256
00:13:03.090 --> 00:13:05.160
These are your biologics.

257
00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:08.670
So most of them are TNF-alpha inhibitors.

258
00:13:08.670 --> 00:13:13.320
Orencia is, the last one, there is not a TNF-alpha biologic,

259
00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:16.080
it's a T-cell inhibitor.

260
00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:19.350
There are some newer classes of biologics that are emerging.

261
00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:21.750
There's some anti-CD20.

262
00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:26.750
Once the anti-T-cell inhibitors, those are emerging,

263
00:13:27.150 --> 00:13:31.937
but these are the work horses of the biologic agents.

264
00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:35.610
None of them is superior to another.

265
00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:38.853
So it doesn't really matter which one you start.

266
00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:42.990
Most importantly, it's which one their insurance company

267
00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:44.133
will afford.

268
00:13:45.660 --> 00:13:47.400
If you're gonna start a biologic agent,

269
00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:48.750
and it's okay to start.

270
00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:51.870
So the patient comes in, you've given them steroids.

271
00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:54.630
At six weeks, they're still flared,

272
00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:57.510
and you're a little trepidatious about starting

273
00:13:57.510 --> 00:14:01.170
triple therapy and you want to add a biologic agent.

274
00:14:01.170 --> 00:14:04.050
It's okay to use a non-biologic agent

275
00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:06.930
and a biologic agent together.

276
00:14:06.930 --> 00:14:08.280
That is okay.

277
00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:11.880
You don't, however, wanna use two biologic agents

278
00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:13.260
at the same time.

279
00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:17.970
So you would never use Enbrel or Remicade at the same time.

280
00:14:17.970 --> 00:14:19.590
No insurance company would pay for it anyway.

281
00:14:19.590 --> 00:14:23.280
But you wanna avoid using two biologics together.

282
00:14:23.280 --> 00:14:24.690
If you're gonna start a biologic agent,

283
00:14:24.690 --> 00:14:27.030
you need to really do four things.

284
00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:28.470
You need to check a PPD,

285
00:14:28.470 --> 00:14:31.170
'cause the TB could be reactivated.

286
00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:33.270
You wanna check it hep B.

287
00:14:33.270 --> 00:14:36.003
You also wanna consider checking a hep C.

288
00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:40.710
And if your patient has a history of melanoma,

289
00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:43.260
you should do send them to derm,

290
00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:45.330
or do an exhaustive exam,

291
00:14:45.330 --> 00:14:48.060
because there is a slight increased risk

292
00:14:48.060 --> 00:14:50.310
of melanoma reactivation in a patient

293
00:14:50.310 --> 00:14:52.410
who's had previous history of skin cancer.

294
00:14:53.430 --> 00:14:55.170
Here are your practice recommendations

295
00:14:55.170 --> 00:14:57.720
that kind of sum those things up.

296
00:14:57.720 --> 00:15:02.193
Again, no regimen of monotherapy is superior to any other.

297
00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:07.890
Don't forget your cardiovascular disease.

298
00:15:07.890 --> 00:15:09.363
This associated with RA.

299
00:15:10.950 --> 00:15:15.950
So this is a category that the major spondyloarthropathies

300
00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:19.071
that they're sort of, I don't know, it might,

301
00:15:19.071 --> 00:15:21.840
they're difficult to put into a box,

302
00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:23.580
because they're very different.

303
00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:26.160
But they are put into this bucket,

304
00:15:26.160 --> 00:15:29.970
because they can all potentially affect the spine

305
00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:31.590
to some degree.

306
00:15:31.590 --> 00:15:33.540
But they're very unique.

307
00:15:33.540 --> 00:15:34.830
These are the primary ones,

308
00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:37.200
and we'll go through each of them.

309
00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.180
So ankylosing spondylitis.

310
00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:41.640
If there's gonna be a spondyloarthropathy question

311
00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:43.500
on the boards, it's gonna be this one.

312
00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:45.210
It's the number one.

313
00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.400
The prevalence is low,

314
00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:51.060
but it's still number one at 0.1 to .2%.

315
00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:52.140
This is the disease.

316
00:15:52.140 --> 00:15:56.400
You probably remember the HLA-B27 that can be associated

317
00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:59.760
with this spondyloarthropathy.

318
00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:04.760
In fact, 95% of people who have ankylosing spondylitis

319
00:16:05.040 --> 00:16:09.870
are positive for HLA-B27, 95%.

320
00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:13.410
However, of all of you who have,

321
00:16:13.410 --> 00:16:18.410
who are positive for HLA-B27, you just have a 1% risk

322
00:16:18.540 --> 00:16:21.273
of developing ankylosing spondylitis.

323
00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:24.690
Caucasians have a greater prevalence.

324
00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:29.690
There's a 10% of Caucasians are positive for HLA-B27,

325
00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:35.163
and 2% of African Americans are positive for HLA-B27.

326
00:16:36.600 --> 00:16:39.210
The symptomology is very consistent with this description

327
00:16:39.210 --> 00:16:41.520
that the pain starts in your lower back.

328
00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:44.730
It's insidious, it can radiate to the glute.

329
00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:48.063
Oftentimes worse in the morning, improves with activity,

330
00:16:49.290 --> 00:16:52.770
but they can also have nocturnal symptoms.

331
00:16:52.770 --> 00:16:55.413
Enthesitis is very common.

332
00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:59.790
So enthesitis is where the tendon joins,

333
00:16:59.790 --> 00:17:01.620
connects with the bone.

334
00:17:01.620 --> 00:17:05.880
And so it's that interface that can be inflamed

335
00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:09.030
most commonly with ankylosing spondylitis.

336
00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:10.680
You can also see eye issues.

337
00:17:10.680 --> 00:17:15.360
So that's a common board question, sort of star is the eye,

338
00:17:15.360 --> 00:17:17.640
the anterior uveitis.

339
00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:21.510
And people respond very quickly initially with NSAIDs,

340
00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:24.030
so that could be sort of a diagnostic

341
00:17:24.030 --> 00:17:25.260
that could help you with a diagnosis.

342
00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:27.690
So if you put them on high dose NSAIDs

343
00:17:27.690 --> 00:17:30.720
on the Friday afternoon, and they get better on Monday,

344
00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:32.910
that's a good indicator that this could be

345
00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:34.830
ankylosing spondylitis.

346
00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:37.410
If they have progressive joint disease,

347
00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:39.900
you don't obviously wanna keep them on NSAIDs forever,

348
00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:42.123
you're gonna use a biologic agent.

349
00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:46.290
So that is ankylosing spondylitis.

350
00:17:46.290 --> 00:17:49.110
This person is a 35-year-old with a three-month history

351
00:17:49.110 --> 00:17:52.590
of an asymmetric polyarthritis

352
00:17:52.590 --> 00:17:54.990
that's noted in six separate joints.

353
00:17:54.990 --> 00:17:57.930
And on exam, you see the pitting of the fingernails

354
00:17:57.930 --> 00:18:01.560
along with a scaly silver rash on both elbows.

355
00:18:01.560 --> 00:18:04.980
Which treatment has been shown to delay further progression

356
00:18:04.980 --> 00:18:06.273
of these joint erosions.

357
00:18:08.190 --> 00:18:10.620
Etanercept, that's Enbrel.

358
00:18:10.620 --> 00:18:15.620
Methotrexate, naproxen, or sulfasalazine.

359
00:18:23.081 --> 00:18:23.914
Good.

360
00:18:24.990 --> 00:18:27.510
Basically you have a decision-making point

361
00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:32.510
between a biologic, a non-biologic, an NSAID,

362
00:18:32.700 --> 00:18:34.230
and essentially another NSAID.

363
00:18:34.230 --> 00:18:36.510
So you can get rid of C and D, get rid of those.

364
00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:39.690
So then what is always gonna be more potent,

365
00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:43.380
a biologic agent versus a non-biologic agent?

366
00:18:43.380 --> 00:18:45.360
Usually the biologic agents will,

367
00:18:45.360 --> 00:18:47.820
will generally always be more potent.

368
00:18:47.820 --> 00:18:52.820
So it is the best for decreasing joint erosions.

369
00:18:53.700 --> 00:18:57.360
These are hallmark features of psoriatic arthritis.

370
00:18:57.360 --> 00:18:59.790
You see the pitting in the nails.

371
00:18:59.790 --> 00:19:03.799
You see the oligoarthritis.

372
00:19:03.799 --> 00:19:06.870
Oligoarthritis means the distal extremities

373
00:19:06.870 --> 00:19:07.980
commonly in the hands,

374
00:19:07.980 --> 00:19:10.533
the dactylitis that you see with this patient.

375
00:19:12.810 --> 00:19:17.810
Most of the time, it's an asymmetric oligoarticular process.

376
00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:21.123
But the nail changes are very common.

377
00:19:22.470 --> 00:19:24.930
This can look like rheumatoid arthritis,

378
00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:27.390
but there are no rheumatoid nodules

379
00:19:27.390 --> 00:19:29.550
that you would see with RA.

380
00:19:29.550 --> 00:19:32.460
And that the disease can be rapidly destructive.

381
00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:35.730
So this is a disease process that also demands

382
00:19:35.730 --> 00:19:38.310
like very acute intervention.

383
00:19:38.310 --> 00:19:40.350
And because it's a spondyloarthropathy,

384
00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:43.560
you're gonna have axial involvement as well.

385
00:19:43.560 --> 00:19:45.123
HIV can make it worse.

386
00:19:47.580 --> 00:19:50.730
So not every psoriatic arthritic patient

387
00:19:50.730 --> 00:19:55.350
will have the presence of psoriasis by itself,

388
00:19:55.350 --> 00:20:00.350
but up to 20% of people who have psoriasis

389
00:20:03.060 --> 00:20:06.480
can develop the arthritic process.

390
00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:10.410
So typically the psoriasis precedes the arthritic process,

391
00:20:10.410 --> 00:20:13.410
and up to 75% of times,

392
00:20:13.410 --> 00:20:16.038
nail changes is noted are very prevalent.

393
00:20:16.038 --> 00:20:18.660
Dactylitis, uveitis are very prevalent.

394
00:20:18.660 --> 00:20:21.810
There's no difference in like the run of the mill psoriasis

395
00:20:21.810 --> 00:20:23.310
and the psoriasis that you would see

396
00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:25.470
with a psoriatic arthritis.

397
00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:26.940
It's exactly the same.

398
00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:29.220
The same places that you would see psoriasis,

399
00:20:29.220 --> 00:20:31.500
you see them with psoriatic arthritis.

400
00:20:31.500 --> 00:20:36.000
So the scalp, extensor surfaces, anal cleft, umbilicus,

401
00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:36.833
et cetera.

402
00:20:38.010 --> 00:20:39.600
This is a good review slide.

403
00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:42.030
Go ahead and put a star on that to come back

404
00:20:42.030 --> 00:20:43.530
that this is how you risk stratify

405
00:20:43.530 --> 00:20:46.650
with a point system psoriatic arthritis.

406
00:20:46.650 --> 00:20:49.860
And again, start your treatment early,

407
00:20:49.860 --> 00:20:52.890
DMARDs are the most effective,

408
00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:54.840
the biologic ones in particular.

409
00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:56.493
If you don't have access to the biologics,

410
00:20:56.493 --> 00:20:59.250
then the non-biologics can be helpful.

411
00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:03.483
And NSAIDs can also be helpful in the short term.

412
00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:07.063
How about reactive arthritides?

413
00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:10.050
The reactive arthritides I feel like we,

414
00:21:10.050 --> 00:21:10.883
I don't know about you all,

415
00:21:10.883 --> 00:21:14.250
but I feel like we saw a lot more of them during COVID.

416
00:21:14.250 --> 00:21:16.800
They seem to be more common.

417
00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:19.548
The Reiter's triad is that classic one.

418
00:21:19.548 --> 00:21:21.990
Can't pee, can't see, can't climb a tree.

419
00:21:21.990 --> 00:21:24.390
So the urethritis, the conjunctivitis,

420
00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:26.040
and then the arthritis.

421
00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:29.070
Usually the symptoms begin just one to four weeks

422
00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:34.070
after whatever infection preceded those infections

423
00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:38.730
are commonly ones that can be associated

424
00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:40.590
with bloody diarrhea.

425
00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:44.760
So that will be Salmonella, Shigella, Yersinia, et cetera.

426
00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:46.773
Chlamydia is also a big player.

427
00:21:47.820 --> 00:21:48.960
Usually it's asymmetric,

428
00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:51.393
and usually it affects multiple joints.

429
00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:56.910
Here are the recommendations that you can go back

430
00:21:56.910 --> 00:22:00.603
to take a look at them as a review.

431
00:22:02.610 --> 00:22:06.270
So typically, these are interestingly,

432
00:22:06.270 --> 00:22:09.660
they're typically provoked by a bacterial etiology.

433
00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:13.290
However, antibiotics have never been shown

434
00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:16.830
to be effective for reactive arthritis.

435
00:22:16.830 --> 00:22:18.990
Almost everything else has been shown to be effective

436
00:22:18.990 --> 00:22:20.730
with a reactive arthritis.

437
00:22:20.730 --> 00:22:24.150
So that includes a biologic agents, that includes steroids,

438
00:22:24.150 --> 00:22:25.653
that includes NSAIDs.

439
00:22:27.660 --> 00:22:31.170
Here's an older gentleman, previous painter.

440
00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:34.260
He comes in with chronic right dull hand pain.

441
00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:36.990
States his DIPs and PIPs are the most tender.

442
00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:39.870
So those your distal interphalangeal joints

443
00:22:39.870 --> 00:22:43.230
in your proximal interphalangeal joints.

444
00:22:43.230 --> 00:22:44.760
But not his MCP.

445
00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:47.250
So here's your MCP.

446
00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:50.400
On exam, there's mild swelling in the DIP/PIP distribution,

447
00:22:50.400 --> 00:22:53.340
but no rubor, no calor.

448
00:22:53.340 --> 00:22:55.860
It's not hot, it's not inflamed.

449
00:22:55.860 --> 00:22:57.510
Which of the following is not consistent

450
00:22:57.510 --> 00:22:59.190
with this diagnosis?

451
00:22:59.190 --> 00:23:00.690
Osteophytes?

452
00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:02.943
Changes in the joint alignment?

453
00:23:03.930 --> 00:23:05.880
Heberden's nodes?

454
00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:09.780
Or MCP inflammation?

455
00:23:09.780 --> 00:23:12.000
So this is a question asking you to differentiate

456
00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:15.183
between OA and RA.

457
00:23:16.290 --> 00:23:18.140
And it's okay, you can use your hand.

458
00:23:23.370 --> 00:23:24.203
Good, good.

459
00:23:24.203 --> 00:23:27.390
So this is a very commonly board-type question.

460
00:23:27.390 --> 00:23:32.390
So the MCP inflammation here is associated with RA,

461
00:23:34.890 --> 00:23:36.480
not with osteoarthritis.

462
00:23:36.480 --> 00:23:41.183
So DIPs, PIPs, those are associated with osteo.

463
00:23:44.310 --> 00:23:47.670
Osteo is the pathophy is very simple.

464
00:23:47.670 --> 00:23:52.380
It's like the number of Newtons per surface area.

465
00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:54.753
It's a wear and tear process.

466
00:23:55.620 --> 00:23:57.990
So it's not a systemic process.

467
00:23:57.990 --> 00:23:59.610
It's not an inflammatory process.

468
00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:01.833
It's simply a wear and tear process.

469
00:24:03.810 --> 00:24:05.490
So you don't see the systemic findings.

470
00:24:05.490 --> 00:24:07.740
You don't see the rubor, calor.

471
00:24:07.740 --> 00:24:10.500
You don't see the inflamed joints.

472
00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:13.383
And you especially don't see them in the MCP.

473
00:24:14.310 --> 00:24:16.740
Transient stiffness is a hallmark.

474
00:24:16.740 --> 00:24:19.650
It's insidious in its onset overall.

475
00:24:19.650 --> 00:24:21.210
And you see them in your hands,

476
00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:24.180
in your weight-bearing joints, most commonly,

477
00:24:24.180 --> 00:24:26.760
because of the force.

478
00:24:26.760 --> 00:24:29.310
Here's a classic picture of the joint space narrowing

479
00:24:29.310 --> 00:24:31.620
in the hips.

480
00:24:31.620 --> 00:24:33.820
Notice there's not much space there anymore.

481
00:24:35.550 --> 00:24:38.763
Here is the, notice the medial compartment of the knee,

482
00:24:39.870 --> 00:24:42.390
common especially in women

483
00:24:42.390 --> 00:24:45.090
that is classic for osteoarthritis.

484
00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:46.650
You could see the osteophytes

485
00:24:46.650 --> 00:24:50.850
that are starting to burge in there.

486
00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:53.850
So here's the problem, like how do we manage osteoarthritis?

487
00:24:54.690 --> 00:24:55.950
We've heard lots of things,

488
00:24:55.950 --> 00:25:00.950
but you know, the best mechanism is gonna be an NSAID.

489
00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:02.670
But you don't wanna do NSAIDs forever.

490
00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:04.830
So using transdermal NSAIDs

491
00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:08.100
really is the first line of defense.

492
00:25:08.100 --> 00:25:11.310
Acetaminophen is equal to placebo.

493
00:25:11.310 --> 00:25:16.140
There's no benefit to using acetaminophen with an NSAID

494
00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:18.990
for chronic osteoarthritis.

495
00:25:18.990 --> 00:25:20.100
We hear lots of things, right?

496
00:25:20.100 --> 00:25:23.880
But there's no benefit to using acetaminophen

497
00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:26.130
for chronic osteoarthritis.

498
00:25:26.130 --> 00:25:28.710
Walking aids, weight loss, physiotherapy,

499
00:25:28.710 --> 00:25:30.560
all these things can be very helpful.

500
00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.293
And we'll come back to injections too.

501
00:25:35.361 --> 00:25:37.890
So topical NSAIDs are most likely

502
00:25:37.890 --> 00:25:40.740
the most effective in the long term,

503
00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:43.923
because we don't wanna use NSAIDs for the long term orally.

504
00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:46.983
Acupuncture, some benefit there.

505
00:25:48.395 --> 00:25:49.710
And then the question always is,

506
00:25:49.710 --> 00:25:51.660
what about steroid injections?

507
00:25:51.660 --> 00:25:52.650
What about Synvisc?

508
00:25:52.650 --> 00:25:55.860
What about hyaluronic acid injections?

509
00:25:55.860 --> 00:25:57.510
The data is just not good.

510
00:25:57.510 --> 00:25:59.460
The data is not great.

511
00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:02.610
There's some beneficial data in the very, very short term

512
00:26:02.610 --> 00:26:06.810
for steroid injections in large weight-bearing joints.

513
00:26:06.810 --> 00:26:10.800
But there's very little data for hyaluronic acid.

514
00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:15.800
In fact, the AAFP does not endorse using hyaluronic acid

515
00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:19.230
for large joint osteoarthritis.

516
00:26:19.230 --> 00:26:20.730
We see it all the time though.

517
00:26:22.290 --> 00:26:24.480
There is some data to show that ultrasound injections,

518
00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:26.850
if you are gonna do an injection in the shoulder,

519
00:26:26.850 --> 00:26:30.180
if you're gonna do one in the hip, even in the knee,

520
00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:33.120
the ultrasound-guided injections can have greater benefit

521
00:26:33.120 --> 00:26:35.100
than non-ultrasound guided injections.

522
00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:38.250
So there's pretty decent data to show

523
00:26:38.250 --> 00:26:39.960
just a little bit of differentiation.

524
00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:41.730
What's not recommended are these.

525
00:26:41.730 --> 00:26:43.620
So put a big star on these.

526
00:26:43.620 --> 00:26:45.030
TENS units.

527
00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:47.520
Glucosamine, chondroitin, we see that all the time.

528
00:26:47.520 --> 00:26:49.500
No data for it.

529
00:26:49.500 --> 00:26:51.660
Acetaminophen, no data for it.

530
00:26:51.660 --> 00:26:54.000
No data for NSAIDs, plus acetaminophen.

531
00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.390
And then very little data for the biologic injections

532
00:26:57.390 --> 00:27:00.240
and for even steroid injections,

533
00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:01.790
certainly not in the long term.

534
00:27:03.660 --> 00:27:06.633
If you're gonna use the NSAID, use a transdermal one first.

535
00:27:07.470 --> 00:27:10.170
So this is coming back to renal stones.

536
00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:11.430
Love it.

537
00:27:11.430 --> 00:27:13.710
53-year-old male with history of renal stones

538
00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:15.780
comes in with a really painful great toe.

539
00:27:15.780 --> 00:27:17.430
I think you know what that is.

540
00:27:17.430 --> 00:27:19.680
Started last night.

541
00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:21.540
He didn't have a fever, no rashes,

542
00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:23.730
no other systemic symptoms.

543
00:27:23.730 --> 00:27:26.370
Which diagnostic feature is most specific

544
00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:28.203
to this inflammatory process?

545
00:27:29.550 --> 00:27:32.673
Is it elevated uric acid greater than 6.8?

546
00:27:33.990 --> 00:27:37.020
Negatively birefringent crystals?

547
00:27:37.020 --> 00:27:39.510
Radiographic evidence of joint erosions?

548
00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:42.033
Or positively birefringent crystals?

549
00:27:43.440 --> 00:27:46.320
This question just keeps coming back, doesn't it?

550
00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:49.713
When is it gonna end, the crystal question?

551
00:27:55.800 --> 00:27:57.120
We got this.

552
00:27:57.120 --> 00:27:58.993
Oh, we didn't get it.

553
00:27:58.993 --> 00:28:00.720
(audience laughing)

554
00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:02.777
So what is this?

555
00:28:02.777 --> 00:28:03.610
<v Audience>Gout?</v>

556
00:28:03.610 --> 00:28:04.443
<v ->It's gout.</v>

557
00:28:04.443 --> 00:28:08.280
So gout forever for the rest of your lives

558
00:28:08.280 --> 00:28:12.450
will always be negatively birefringent crystals.

559
00:28:12.450 --> 00:28:16.680
Pseudogout, which starts with a P, starts with a P.

560
00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:21.450
Pseudogout, P, is the positively birefringent crystals.

561
00:28:21.450 --> 00:28:24.240
So don't even waste a single additional neuron

562
00:28:24.240 --> 00:28:25.073
thinking about that question again,

563
00:28:25.073 --> 00:28:27.210
which you will see again.

564
00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:29.523
But gout is negatively birefringent crystals.

565
00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:31.860
Gout, the disease of kings.

566
00:28:31.860 --> 00:28:35.313
I think that the symptoms you, everybody's well aware of,

567
00:28:36.270 --> 00:28:39.330
the vast majority of initial symptoms are the podagra.

568
00:28:39.330 --> 00:28:41.520
This is greater than 50% of the time.

569
00:28:41.520 --> 00:28:43.533
You don't see the systemic symptoms.

570
00:28:44.730 --> 00:28:46.410
And be very careful,

571
00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:50.340
because 20% of gout patients also have renal stones.

572
00:28:50.340 --> 00:28:51.810
And during the Q and A,

573
00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:54.390
we'll talk a little bit more about renal stones.

574
00:28:54.390 --> 00:28:58.230
But always remember thiazides are great

575
00:28:58.230 --> 00:28:59.820
if you have renal stones,

576
00:28:59.820 --> 00:29:02.523
but they're terrible if you have gout.

577
00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:04.748
Everybody got that?

578
00:29:04.748 --> 00:29:06.600
<v Audience>Yeah.</v>

579
00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:08.820
<v ->These are the four stages of gout.</v>

580
00:29:08.820 --> 00:29:10.800
You can go back and take a look.

581
00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:13.410
You know, it takes a while for the uric acid to build up

582
00:29:13.410 --> 00:29:16.230
before you eventually start having degradation

583
00:29:16.230 --> 00:29:18.210
in the joint itself.

584
00:29:18.210 --> 00:29:23.210
And hyperuricemia alone is not sufficient

585
00:29:23.340 --> 00:29:25.590
to make a diagnosis of gout.

586
00:29:25.590 --> 00:29:27.993
You need to see the crystals,

587
00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:31.560
unless they have a history, they've had crystals before.

588
00:29:31.560 --> 00:29:33.450
6.8 is the magic number.

589
00:29:33.450 --> 00:29:37.450
It's at that point the crystals start to diffuse out

590
00:29:38.490 --> 00:29:40.440
into the joint space.

591
00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:45.090
So your goal, uric acid is less than six.

592
00:29:45.090 --> 00:29:46.383
That's your goal.

593
00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:49.983
There we go, negatively birefringent crystals.

594
00:29:51.570 --> 00:29:52.890
A little bit about pseudogout.

595
00:29:52.890 --> 00:29:54.750
Sometimes it's very hard to distinguish

596
00:29:54.750 --> 00:29:57.090
between pseudogout and gout.

597
00:29:57.090 --> 00:30:01.173
Oftentimes precipitated by illness, stress, surgery,

598
00:30:02.370 --> 00:30:05.580
more commonly associated with the knee rather than the toe.

599
00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:07.892
So that's a good one to remember.

600
00:30:07.892 --> 00:30:10.380
But it could also be in any joint.

601
00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:12.573
So that could be confusing too.

602
00:30:13.710 --> 00:30:15.240
So what causes gout?

603
00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:16.800
You hear lots of things.

604
00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:18.480
Don't drink, don't eat a lot of meat.

605
00:30:18.480 --> 00:30:20.790
Those things can be true.

606
00:30:20.790 --> 00:30:22.290
Here, you're relative risk for,

607
00:30:22.290 --> 00:30:24.120
if you have a high protein diet,

608
00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:28.050
but it's actually high fructose corn syrup

609
00:30:28.050 --> 00:30:32.340
that puts you at the greatest risk of having gout.

610
00:30:32.340 --> 00:30:35.850
So obesity, high fructose corn syrup diet,

611
00:30:35.850 --> 00:30:38.460
overall, too much energy substrate

612
00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:41.673
that you're consuming can put you at a greater risk of gout.

613
00:30:42.690 --> 00:30:44.220
How many of you have a patient

614
00:30:44.220 --> 00:30:46.683
on one of these antihypertensives?

615
00:30:48.132 --> 00:30:49.560
(Benjamin laughs)

616
00:30:49.560 --> 00:30:50.670
All of them, right?

617
00:30:50.670 --> 00:30:52.440
So this is a great slide to remember,

618
00:30:52.440 --> 00:30:57.060
because losartan and calcium channel blockers

619
00:30:57.060 --> 00:30:59.280
are the two anti-hypertensives

620
00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:02.130
that you wanna turn to every time.

621
00:31:02.130 --> 00:31:04.440
Losartan and amlodipine.

622
00:31:04.440 --> 00:31:07.890
Those are the two anti-hypertensives that are preferential.

623
00:31:07.890 --> 00:31:11.340
All of the others, especially the thiazides,

624
00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:15.123
you want to avoid if you have a patient with suspected gout.

625
00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:18.503
There's pretty big numbers relative risk of 2.4.

626
00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:21.810
So this is a slide that oftentimes

627
00:31:21.810 --> 00:31:24.360
people have a little bit of confusion.

628
00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:26.430
And I think this is a great learning opportunity

629
00:31:26.430 --> 00:31:30.090
in this moment, because we make this mistake,

630
00:31:30.090 --> 00:31:32.550
our residents make this mistake all the time.

631
00:31:32.550 --> 00:31:36.090
Someone has an acute gout flare,

632
00:31:36.090 --> 00:31:38.850
and you start treatment on a Friday afternoon.

633
00:31:38.850 --> 00:31:41.700
Normally you're gonna start with whatever you have,

634
00:31:41.700 --> 00:31:44.310
colchicine, NSAIDs, steroids.

635
00:31:44.310 --> 00:31:48.060
All of those things are equally efficacious.

636
00:31:48.060 --> 00:31:50.940
However, you don't wanna treat someone with steroids

637
00:31:50.940 --> 00:31:52.260
for six months.

638
00:31:52.260 --> 00:31:53.990
You don't wanna treat someone with NSAIDs for six months.

639
00:31:53.990 --> 00:31:58.260
So colchicine actually is the best initiating medicine

640
00:31:58.260 --> 00:32:00.363
for acute prophylaxis.

641
00:32:01.200 --> 00:32:03.570
A lot of people will stop the acute prophylaxis,

642
00:32:03.570 --> 00:32:06.810
whatever NSAID, anti-inflammatory you use,

643
00:32:06.810 --> 00:32:08.880
after they come back maybe in a month.

644
00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:10.440
But the data is this.

645
00:32:10.440 --> 00:32:14.730
The data is to treat with acute anti-inflammatories

646
00:32:14.730 --> 00:32:16.293
for the better of six months.

647
00:32:17.460 --> 00:32:18.300
If you're gonna remember one thing,

648
00:32:18.300 --> 00:32:20.940
just treat for six months with anti-inflammatories

649
00:32:20.940 --> 00:32:25.410
after that flare, or be evidence to treat for three months

650
00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:29.163
after you've achieved a target goal of uric acid.

651
00:32:30.090 --> 00:32:32.520
We're certainly six months after achieving

652
00:32:32.520 --> 00:32:35.284
target goal of uric acid if you have tophi.

653
00:32:35.284 --> 00:32:38.580
So tophi will indicate, you know, more severe disease.

654
00:32:38.580 --> 00:32:43.440
So continue your colchicine for six months.

655
00:32:43.440 --> 00:32:44.610
Another learning point.

656
00:32:44.610 --> 00:32:47.640
There's no great benefit of high dose colchicine

657
00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:49.350
compared to low dose colchicine.

658
00:32:49.350 --> 00:32:50.490
They're the same.

659
00:32:50.490 --> 00:32:52.890
You just get more GI side effects,

660
00:32:52.890 --> 00:32:54.420
the more you increase the dose.

661
00:32:54.420 --> 00:32:56.970
So it's okay to start with, you know,

662
00:32:56.970 --> 00:33:00.030
two tablets of colchicine per day.

663
00:33:00.030 --> 00:33:02.130
And then after they've been stable for a while,

664
00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:06.030
you just decrease them to one tablet of colchicine per day

665
00:33:06.030 --> 00:33:09.870
with or without your uric acid lowering agent.

666
00:33:09.870 --> 00:33:14.070
So this is when you should use a uric acid lowering agent.

667
00:33:14.070 --> 00:33:16.140
And the number one uric acid lowering agent

668
00:33:16.140 --> 00:33:18.810
is still allopurinol.

669
00:33:18.810 --> 00:33:23.700
You don't need to use Uloric febuxostat.

670
00:33:23.700 --> 00:33:25.620
So if you have tophi, if you have frequent attacks

671
00:33:25.620 --> 00:33:27.510
greater than two per year, if you have kidney disease,

672
00:33:27.510 --> 00:33:29.400
if you have gout with kidney stones,

673
00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:32.253
then you need to use a uric acid lowering agent.

674
00:33:33.330 --> 00:33:34.980
Here are the American College

675
00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:36.510
of Rheumatology recommendations,

676
00:33:36.510 --> 00:33:39.183
which kinda sum up what we just talked about.

677
00:33:42.690 --> 00:33:43.890
And that is it for that.

678
00:33:43.890 --> 00:33:46.290
I just wanna make one note.

679
00:33:46.290 --> 00:33:48.300
When you are using allopurinol,

680
00:33:48.300 --> 00:33:50.220
the great risk of allopurinol

681
00:33:50.220 --> 00:33:52.590
as a type one hypersensitivity reaction,

682
00:33:52.590 --> 00:33:56.550
and that can happen in 1% of cases.

683
00:33:56.550 --> 00:33:59.340
And of those 1%, some of them die.

684
00:33:59.340 --> 00:34:02.190
So allopurinol can be a dangerous drug.

685
00:34:02.190 --> 00:34:04.140
There's a new genetic marker.

686
00:34:04.140 --> 00:34:08.523
So there's a much greater risk in folks who come from Asia.

687
00:34:10.020 --> 00:34:11.910
And there's a genetic test that you can do

688
00:34:11.910 --> 00:34:16.500
for a very specific HLA-5801 marker.

689
00:34:16.500 --> 00:34:19.500
And that can help tell you if you have that gene.

690
00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:21.210
If you don't have the gene, use allopurinol.

691
00:34:21.210 --> 00:34:22.920
If you do have that gene,

692
00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:26.400
that's when you would use the Uloric.

693
00:34:26.400 --> 00:34:29.370
Otherwise, just use allopurinol.

694
00:34:29.370 --> 00:34:33.153
Start with 100 milligrams and then titrate slowly.

695
00:34:34.470 --> 00:34:36.900
I think it's time now for some questions.

696
00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:39.120
In the back, there are some supplemental slides

697
00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:41.040
that have a little bit more about

698
00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:43.140
some of the other nuanced tests

699
00:34:43.140 --> 00:34:47.250
that you might use for SLE, et cetera,

700
00:34:47.250 --> 00:34:50.817
that can guide you in that way.

701
00:34:50.817 --> 00:34:53.400
(gentle music)

